{
    "blocks": [
        {
            "id": "intro_looping_lists",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Looping & Checking Lists",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "One of the most common things you'll do with lists is go through each item one by one. You'll also often need to check if a specific item exists in a list."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Python makes both of these tasks simple with `for` loops and the `in` operator."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "looping_through_lists",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Looping Through Lists",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can use a `for` loop to go through each item in a list. The loop variable takes the value of each item, one at a time."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "fruits = [\"apple\", \"banana\", \"orange\"]\nfor fruit in fruits:\n    print(fruit)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "apple\nbanana\norange"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The loop goes through each item in `fruits`, and `fruit` takes the value of each item one by one."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "loop_variable_name",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can name the loop variable anything you want. It's common to use the singular form of the list name."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "colors = [\"red\", \"green\", \"blue\"]\nfor color in colors:\n    print(f\"I like {color}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "I like red\nI like green\nI like blue"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Using `color` for the loop variable makes the code easy to read."
                }
            ]
        },
